SIMPLE: elongation
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Elongation
<hw>E`lon*ga"tion</hw> <pr>(?; 277)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[LL.
<ets>elongatio</ets>: cf. F. <ets>⟦eacute⟧longation</ets>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of lengthening, or the state of being
lengthened; protraction; extension.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Elongation</xex>
of the fibers.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Arbuthnot.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>That which lengthens out; continuation.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>May not the mountains of Westmoreland and Cumberland be considered
as <qex>elongations</qex> of these two chains?</q>
<rj><qau>Pinkerton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Removal to a distance; withdrawal; a being at a
distance; distance.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The distant points in the celestial expanse appear to the eye in
so small a degree of <qex>elongation</qex> from one another, as bears no
proportion to what is real.</q> <rj><qau>Glanvill.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Astron.)</fld> <def>The angular distance of a
planet from the sun; <as>as, the <ex>elongation</ex> of Venus or
Mercury</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Elope</ent>⟦br⟧
